xvsRI-ZC0feWCiNohBbQaKHry1bhoAoGLWrFirJPZSv-i_4BznSATQ], the co-founder and=
 President of Eco [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEGOwyAMRU9TlhFxgMK=
CxWzmGoiAJ0UlkAKZKLcf2ixGsmxZX_bXf842XHI59ZZrI-9m2rmhTnjUiK1hIXvFYoLXowA5ca=
aI18yPkksSqvkpiKsNUbeyI9n2OQZnW8jpc0EpcPLQ3qOgbpq4B84pg4nCqKRSzM9cSKkuX7v7g=
Mmhxl8sZ05Ion60ttXb9HWD717HcQzo8uDy2jcSNFAAOo1sBM6ADTCMzkrGFFN45xIZDN4d8SWW=
48bousBQ97k2657vF6TolNucS0hLl58Pu2L8CD2G6XPdU2inwWTniP5K2C5Qn8xmwYSlA_TGto6=
H3UEAuwsQ9ErUEfBOQADlpDv73K_Sv-kf2AN-Ng] and the person who introduced me t=
o Andrew, co-led Fount=E2=80=99s pre-seed with Founders Fund. He shared the=
 investment memo that he wrote at the time, in which he described Andrew=E2=
=80=99s upbringing and education:=C2=A0
Andrew was born to a gastroenterologist father and a mother who worked for =
American Airlines and came from a decorated military family. Unsurprisingly=
, Andrew grew up fascinated by the best parts of medicine and international=
 affairs=E2=80=A6
When applying to college, there was only one program that combined both of =
these interests, while also offering daily access to opportunities for real=
-world experience: the Science, Technology, and International Affairs progr=
am=E2=80=94then an obscure major, but now the most popular =E2=80=94 at Geo=
rgetown=E2=80=99s famed School of Foreign Service in Washington, DC=E2=80=
=A6
Outside the classroom, Andrew worked with several US Government agencies on=
 protecting the U.S. against terrorist and state threats by deploying advan=
ced technologies, in the process winning a full scholarship from the U.S. G=
overnment for his research.=C2=A0
After his full undergrad scholarship, Andrew won another $200k scholarship =
from the government to continue his studies with three concurrent masters: =
Microbiology & Immunology, Health Physics, and Security Studies.=C2=A0
You can read the whole bio section from that memo here [https://email.mg2.s=
ubstack.com/c/eJxFkcFOwzAMhp9muVGlbtJ1hxwQGmJXBAJxqdLEawNp0qUuYzw92XpAshMrv=
60_-mw0YR_TRU1xJnY9WrpMqAKeZ49EmNgyY2qdVWUNTSXFjlklbNnIhrm5PSbEUTuvKC3IpqXz=
zmhyMdwmOAfJBlUdpeVHUQHnWAoDoKW1ommu-q46dquvXqzDYFDhN6ZLDMi8GoimeVPdb-Axh41=
mLvoYe4-FieP6sowY6FrmLLftd7QPr293vEw_H_qdXk7eDuPT53MwTv7-Hg56GfbD5_Sxz-1oHT=
GngAPwqhQlSAGigKI0uhFiJ3a4lQ0KKKw5-1PdnzeCjz0U89LNpM3X9RMsqRCpi8mFPstfgx7R3=
4QMo833uARHlxaD7jzalROtuG_k2h4DprwG22rKkMUWahDbGmq-cskgZeZYA5csO9uYp8K_6R9c=
Gpcy]. The takeaway is this: Andrew was practically designed in a lab by th=
e U.S. Government to build Fount and fix health and human performance at sc=
ale.
When the Pentagon=E2=80=99s Office of Net Assessment [https://email.mg2.sub=
stack.com/c/eJxFkMGOhCAMhp9mOBpAQD1wmMscdx-BIFSHjIILdY1vv8x42KTpn7b586efswh=
zyqfeUkHybgbPDXSEoyyACJnsBbIJXjPF-1aKgXgtPOtlT0IxUwZYbVg05h3Ito9LcBZDih8HpV=
ySp6ZOwejt0DHZtS0TqmetHJgDybppEvLKtbsPEB1o-IV8pghk0U_Erdza-40_akFsjvAKG_hgm=
5TnunrPVb6nKTgwaTJfgOZeCpSyQkQSNKec0xrKuBRcNLxhzvZCDGKATvYgeOPdsfyo-bgJus68=
KftY0LpX49JKso4Jx5RDnOv59bQrLJ9DfdVUXfcY8DQQ7biAvyjgBfPDxcwQIVfI3lisCEXHFRe=
d4opeX1dMslJSnEpSk32qrvgf-gdtmIxj] needed to hire a researcher =E2=80=9Cwho=
 had a deep knowledge of biology, was just as deep in national security, wh=
o thought creatively, and could also write well,=E2=80=9D he was one of the=
 few people in the country with the right mix of skills and knowledge. He w=
as hired after one interview, and while there, =E2=80=9Cstarted his decade-=
long project to understand what processes in the body he could tap into to =
materially enhance performance and which tools he could use to do this.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0
Over time, Andrew went from developing specific studies and programs to hel=
ping the Department of Defense leadership invest its multi-billion dollar R=
&D budget, with a focus on human performance, synthetic biology, and AI. Al=
l the while, he continued to work with Special Ops personnel =E2=80=93 peop=
le for whom a .01% improvement in performance can be the difference between=
 life and death - giving Andrew both the 30,000 foot view and the one inch =
view.
After working with the military for eight years, Andrew entered the private=
 sector in 2017. His accolades and accomplishments during and since are abs=
urd. More are listed in the doc, but a couple:=C2=A0
U.S. Army Mad Scientist distinction =E2=80=93 twice
Adjunct professorship at Georgetown=E2=80=99s Security Studies Graduate Pro=
gram
Johns Hopkins Emerging Leaders in Biosecurity Fellowship=C2=A0
Hired by the Miami Heat, USA Soccer, and billionaires as performance adviso=
r
Wired described [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMGOhSAMRb_msRsDtSIuW=
MxmfsMg9PnIKDiIQ_z74elikqbNTdPe3GNNpjmmU29xz-zdxnxupAOVfaGcKbFjpzR6p4UE1XY4=
MKfRCdUp5vfxmYhW4xed00FsO6bFW5N9DNcF59Cxl5YcnwYNHwQoJVU79WRRDYOzoueDaW9fczh=
PwZKmX0pnDMQW_cp52x_t5wO-apVSmuITucbGtWrgAuq4mgkuUfl4UUpVMa-BA_BWoIAOARtohD=
UKccCB-k4RQuNsWX7kXB7I1xma_Zj2bOz3-zlLOsQ8xeTDXNffL7PSci1qxLHO9Qg-nyMFMy3k7=
vT5hnjxGGcKlCpcN5pc0WEPErCXIPmdtuLpKh0JvGPV2cV6Ff5N_wC_rIbY] Andrew=E2=80=
=99s work as giving our soldiers mutant powers!=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s put things in perspective here. The US Military=E2=80=99s ann=
ual budget in 2021 was $778 billion. Behind Social Security and Health spen=
ding, it=E2=80=99s the largest budget in the US, and the largest discretion=
ary budget bar none, likely in the world. And the US Government chose Andre=
w to lead cutting edge human performance and biotech efforts for that milit=
ary, putting the performance of the world=E2=80=99s most expensive and adva=
nced soldiers in his hands.=C2=A0
While the military is rigid in certain areas, it doesn=E2=80=99t subscribe =
to any orthodoxy when it comes to the performance of its soldiers. It=E2=80=
=99s the best-funded human performance lab in the world, and it offers an a=
dditional benefit beyond the money: soldiers who, unlike normal trial parti=
cipants, want to comply with any programs or experiments that could enhance=
 them.
Andrew=E2=80=99s experience improving human performance from within the gov=
ernment=E2=80=99s third-highest spend category gave him the skills necessar=
y to try to dramatically improve results and lower costs in its highest: he=
althcare.=C2=A0
In 2019, he launched Fount to rethink health from the ground up. He=E2=80=
=99s raised money from funds including Founders Fund, Not Boring Capital, A=
llen & Co., and Elysian Park (the LA Dodgers=E2=80=99 fund), to tackle it. =
And =E2=80=93 to use a very on-the-nose baseball pun =E2=80=93 he=E2=80=99s=
 in like the second inning.=C2=A0
Fount as it stands today is just a way to fund the really big goal.=C2=A0
The Elon Musk Company Formula=C2=A0
Elon Musk hasn=E2=80=99t touched healthcare yet, but I imagine that if he d=
id, it=E2=80=99s unlikely he=E2=80=99d try to fix it from inside the health=
care system.=C2=A0
In the Neuralink post, Urban wrote about Musk=E2=80=99s new company thought=
 process:=C2=A0
His initial thinking about a new company always starts on the right and wor=
ks its way left. He decides that some specific change in the world will inc=
rease the likelihood of humanity having the best possible future.=C2=A0
He knows that large-scale world change happens quickest when the whole worl=
d=E2=80=94the Human Colossus=E2=80=94is working on it. And he knows that th=
e Human Colossus will work toward a goal if (and only if) there=E2=80=99s a=
n economic forcing function in place=E2=80=94if it=E2=80=99s a good busines=
s decision to spend resources innovating toward that goal.
Fixing healthcare from the individual level up fits the bill.=C2=A0
